      <section type="section">
          <title>Impulse</title>
          <shortcode>ESBFJ</shortcode>
          <para>Impulse is the product of the net force and the time interval for which the force acts. Impulse is defined as:</para>
          

          <latex>\mathrm{Impulse}=F·\Delta t</latex>
          

          <para>However, from Newton's Second Law, we know that</para>
          

          <latex display='block'>
\begin{align}
 F&amp; = \frac{\Delta p}{\Delta t} \\ 
 \therefore F·\Delta t&amp; = \Delta p \\ 
&amp; = \text{Impulse} 
\end{align}</latex>
          

          <para>Therefore,</para>
          

          <latex>\mathrm{Impulse}=\Delta p</latex>
          

          <para>Impulse is equal to the change in momentum of an object. From this equation we see, that for a given change in momentum, <latex>{F}_{net}\Delta t</latex> is fixed. Thus, if <latex>{F}_{net}</latex> is reduced, <latex>\Delta t</latex> must be increased (i.e. a smaller resultant force must be applied for longer to bring about the same change in momentum). Alternatively if <latex>\Delta t</latex> is reduced (i.e. the resultant force is applied for a shorter period) then the resultant force must be increased to bring about the same change in momentum.</para>
		  <para> The graph below show how the force acting on a body changes with time.</para>
		  <image style:width='0.4'>
				<src>photos/Fvstgraphtofindimpulse.JPG</src>
				
				</image>
				<para> The area under the graph, given by Ft, represents the impulse of the body. </para>
          <worked_example>
            <title>Impulse and Change in momentum</title>
			
            <question>
              <para>A <unit_number><number>150</number><unit>N</unit></unit_number> resultant force acts on a <unit_number><number>300</number><unit>kg</unit></unit_number> trailer. Calculate how long it takes this force to change the trailer's velocity from <unit_number><number>2</number><unit>m·s<sup>-1</sup></unit></unit_number> to <unit_number><number>6</number><unit>m·s<sup>-1</sup></unit></unit_number> in the same direction. Assume that the forces acts to the right.</para>
            </question>
            <answer>
              <workstep>
                <title>Identify what information is given and what is asked for</title>
                <para>The question explicitly gives</para>
                <list list-type="bulleted">
                  <item>
                    <para>the trailer's mass as <unit_number><number>300</number><unit>kg</unit></unit_number>,</para>
                  </item>
                  <item>
                    <para>the trailer's initial velocity as <unit_number><number>2</number><unit>m·s<sup>-1</sup></unit></unit_number> to the right,</para>
                  </item>
                  <item>
                    <para>the trailer's final velocity as <unit_number><number>6</number><unit>m·s<sup>-1</sup></unit></unit_number> to the right, and</para>
                  </item>
                  <item>
                    <para>the resultant force acting on the object</para>
                  </item>
                </list>
                <para>all in the correct units!</para>
                

                <para>We are asked to calculate the time taken <latex>\Delta t</latex> to accelerate the trailer from the <number>2</number> to <unit_number><number>6</number><unit>m·s<sup>-1</sup></unit></unit_number>. From the Law of Momentum,</para>
                

                <latex display='block'>
\begin{align}
 {F}_{net}\Delta t&amp; = \Delta p \\ 
&amp; = m{v}_{f}-m{v}_{i} \\ 
&amp; = m\left({v}_{f}-{v}_{i}\right). 
\end{align}</latex>
                

                <para>Thus we have everything we need to find <latex>\Delta t</latex>!</para>
              </workstep>
              <workstep>
                <title>Choose a frame of reference</title>
                <para>Choose right as the positive direction.</para>
              </workstep>
              <workstep>
                <title>Do the calculation and quote the final answer</title>
                <latex display='block'>
\begin{align}
 {F}_{net}\Delta t&amp; = m\left({v}_{f}-{v}_{i}\right) \\ 
 \left(+150 \mathrm{N}\right)\Delta \mathrm{t}&amp; = \left(300 \text{kg}\right)\left(\left(+6 \text{m}·{\text{s}}^{-1}\right)-\left(+2 \text{m}·{\text{s}}^{-1}\right)\right) \\ 
 \left(+150 \mathrm{N}\right)\Delta \mathrm{t}&amp; = \left(300 \text{kg}\right)\left(+4 \text{m}·{\text{s}}^{-1}\right) \\ 
 \Delta t&amp; = \frac{\left(300 \text{kg}\right)\left(+4 \text{m}·{\text{s}}^{-1}\right)}{+150 \mathrm{N}} \\ 
 \Delta t&amp; = 8 \text{s} 
\end{align}</latex>
                

                <para>It takes <unit_number><number>8</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number> for the force to change the object's velocity from <unit_number><number>2</number><unit>m·s<sup>-1</sup></unit></unit_number> to the right to <unit_number><number>6</number><unit>m·s<sup>-1</sup></unit></unit_number> to the right.</para>
              </workstep>
            </answer>
          </worked_example>
          <worked_example>
            <title>Impulsive cricketers!</title>
            <question>
              <para>A cricket ball weighing <unit_number><number>156</number><unit>g</unit></unit_number> is moving at <unit_number><number>54</number><unit>km·hr<sup>-1</sup></unit></unit_number> towards a batsman. It is hit by the batsman back towards the bowler at <unit_number><number>36</number><unit>km·hr<sup>-1</sup></unit></unit_number>. Calculate</para>
              <list list-type="enumerated">
                <item>
                  <para>the ball's impulse, and</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <para>the average force exerted by the bat if the ball is in contact with the bat for <unit_number><number>0.13</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number>.</para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </question>
            <answer>
              <workstep>
                <title>Identify what information is given and what is asked for</title>
                <para>The question explicitly gives</para>
                <list list-type="bulleted">
                  <item>
                    <para>the ball's mass,</para>
                  </item>
                  <item>
                    <para>the ball's initial velocity,</para>
                  </item>
                  <item>
                    <para>the ball's final velocity, and</para>
                  </item>
                  <item>
                    <para>the time of contact between bat and ball</para>
                  </item>
                </list>
                <para>We are asked to calculate the impulse</para>
                

                <latex>\mathrm{Impulse}=\Delta p={F}_{\mathrm{net}}\Delta t</latex>
                

                <para>Since we do not have the force exerted by the bat on the ball ( <latex>{F}_{\mathrm{net}}</latex>), we have to calculate the impulse from the change in momentum of the ball. Now, since</para>
                

                <latex display='block'>
\begin{align}
 \Delta p&amp; = {p}_{f}-{p}_{i} \\ 
&amp; = m{v}_{f}-m{v}_{i}, 
\end{align}</latex>
                

                <para>we need the ball's mass, initial velocity and final velocity, which we are given.</para>
              </workstep>
              <workstep>
                <title>Convert to S.I. units</title>
                <para>Firstly let us change units for the mass</para>
                

                <latex display='block'>
\begin{align}
 <number>1000</number> \mathrm{g}&amp; = 1 \text{kg} \\ 
 \text{So,} 1 \mathrm{g}&amp; = \frac{1}{<number>1000</number>} \mathrm{kg} \\ 
 \therefore 156\times 1 \mathrm{g}&amp; = 156\times \frac{1}{<number>1000</number>} \mathrm{kg} \\ 
&amp; = <number>0.156</number> \text{kg} 
\end{align}</latex>
                

                <para>Next we change units for the velocity</para>
                

                <latex display='block'>
\begin{align}
 1 \mathrm{km}·{\mathrm{h}}^{-1}&amp; = \frac{<number>1000</number> \mathrm{m}}{<number>3600</number> \text{s}} \\ 
 \therefore 54\times 1 \mathrm{km}·{\mathrm{h}}^{-1}&amp; = 54\times \frac{<number>1000</number> \mathrm{m}}{<number>3600</number> \text{s}} \\ 
&amp; = 15 \text{m}·{\text{s}}^{-1} 
\end{align}</latex>
                

                <para>Similarly, <unit_number><number>36</number><unit>km·hr<sup>-1</sup></unit></unit_number> = <unit_number><number>10</number><unit>m·s<sup>-1</sup></unit></unit_number>.</para>
              </workstep>
              <workstep>
                <title>Choose a frame of reference</title>
                <para>Let us choose the direction from the batsman to the bowler as the positive direction. Then the initial velocity of the ball is <latex>{v}_{i}=-15\text{m}·{\text{s}}^{-1}</latex>, while the final velocity of the ball is <latex>{v}_{f}=10\text{m}·{\text{s}}^{-1}</latex>.</para>
              </workstep>
              <workstep>
                <title>Calculate the momentum</title>
                <para>Now we calculate the change in momentum,</para>
                

                <latex display='block'>
\begin{align}
 p&amp; = {p}_{f}-{p}_{i} \\ 
&amp; = m{v}_{f}-m{v}_{i} \\ 
&amp; = m\left({v}_{f}-{v}_{i}\right) \\ 
&amp; = \left(<number>0.156</number> \text{kg}\right)\left(\left(+10 \text{m}·{\text{s}}^{-1}\right)-\left(-15 \text{m}·{\text{s}}^{-1}\right)\right) \\ 
&amp; = <number>+3.9</number> \text{kg}·\text{m}·{\text{s}}^{-1} \\ 
&amp; = <number>3.9</number> \text{kg}·\text{m}·{\text{s}}^{-1}\text{in the direction from the batsman to the bowler} 
\end{align}</latex>
    
              </workstep>
              <workstep>
                <title>Determine the impulse</title>
                <para>Finally since impulse is just the change in momentum of the ball,</para>
                

                <latex display='block'>
\begin{align}
 \mathrm{Impulse}&amp; = \Delta p \\ 
&amp; = <number>3.9</number> \text{kg}·\text{m}·{\text{s}}^{-1}\text{in the direction from the batsman to the bowler} 
\end{align}</latex>
             
              </workstep>
              <workstep>
                <title>Determine the average force exerted by the bat</title>
                <latex>\mathrm{Impulse}={F}_{net}\Delta t=\Delta p</latex>
                

                <para>We are given <latex>\Delta t</latex> and we have calculated the impulse of the ball.</para>
                

                <latex display='block'>
\begin{align}
 {F}_{net}\Delta t&amp; = \mathrm{Impulse} \\ 
 {F}_{net}\left(<number>0.13</number> \text{s}\right)&amp; = <number>+3.9</number> \mathrm{N}·\text{s} \\ 
 {F}_{net}&amp; = \frac{<number>+3.9</number> \mathrm{N}· \text{s}}{<number>0.13</number> \text{s}} \\ 
&amp; = +30 \mathrm{N} \\ 
&amp; = 30 \mathrm{N} \text{in the direction from the batsman to the bowler} 
\end{align}</latex>
         
              </workstep>
            </answer>
          </worked_example>
